4616272/Environmental-and-human-i-025-thumb-4359.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"Corbis","photographer":"Ed Kashi","altText":"The Curse of Black Gold: Environmental and human impact of oil extraction in Niger Delta, Nigeria","height":"68","credit":"Ed Kashi/Corbis","caption":"People row a boat next to pipelines to the coast terminal run by the Nigerian National Petroleum Company (NNPC) which are marked with evidence of oil leaks and oil fires, Okrika, Rivers.","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-360077957","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":4,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2010/3/5/1267804607614/Environmental-and-human-i-018.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"guardian.co.uk","photographer":"Ed Kashi","altText":"The Curse of Black Gold: Environmental and human impact of oil extraction in Niger Delta, Nigeria","height":"390","credit":"Ed Kashi/Corbis","caption":"A young girl crosses over pipelines that run directly through the town. A troubled area near Port Harcourt, factional fighting is common in Okrika","width":"585"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2010/3/5/1267804607614/Environmental-and-human-i-018-thumb-7189.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"Corbis","photographer":"Ed Kashi","altText":"The Curse of Black Gold: Environmental and human impact of oil extraction in Niger Delta, Nigeria","height":"68","credit":"Ed Kashi/Corbis","caption":"A young girl crosses over NNPC, Nigerian National Petroleum, pipelines that run directly through the community of Okrika, Rivers. A troubled area near Port Harcourt, Okrika has oil, refineries, pipelines and violence. Factional fighting is common here. Fishing is struggling, like in most of the delta, but was once the main source of employment.","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-360077966","relation":"gallery","ty